1. Open the github account.

Create a new repo.

2. Open the git bash on local
              
         git clone url
         git clone https://github.com/sarutig/demo6.git

3. create a new test and save it to the git repo.


         git add .
         git commit -m "done"

4. Modify the existing file >>>>>then   add and commit again

         git status
         git add .
         git commit -m "done2"

and check status with the diagram given in the chat window

5. perform push opertion
    git push origin main
  and then reload the github.
git config --global user.name ""
git config --global user.email ""
============================================================

Q. ON THE GITHUB, CREATE A NEW FILE AND THEN USE PULL OPERATION


 git pull origin main


and finally check the files on to the local folder

Q. Creating branches (i)local
                    (ii)Remote 

======================================================
Q. Publishing branches from local to remote
                  
Q. Fetching branches from remote to local
=====================================================

Creating branches ON REMOTE [GITHUB]

b1 from main

create a file in b1 

now check the no.of files in b1 and main


==============================================================

Creating branches (i)local

git branch b11            [new branch create]

git branch                [to check the no. of branches]

git checkout b11           [ to switch over that branch]


Q. SWITCH OVER THE BRANCHES

Q. USE ls to check the no.of files


Q.  now, on b11 create a text file(testb) >>>add, commit

Q.  now, check the contents of branch b11 and main using ls         command

Q.  Now, create a new local branch b22 from b11


Q. on b22 create a text file(testb2) >>>add, commit


Q.  now, check the contents of branch b22, b11 and main using ls         command

       b22  =
       b11  =
       main =


Q. PUBLISH THIS BRANCH (B11)

     LOCAL BRANCH CAN BE REFLECTED ON THE REMOTE BY USING 
      PUSH OPERATION


       git checkout b11
       git push origin b11

and then reload, the github , then check b11 would be there    


Q. NOW, CHECK ON GITHUB for [b11] THE PULL REQUEST PROCESS.............
    COMPARE, MERGE, CLOSE THE PULL REQUEST


AND FINALLLLLLLLYYYYY

git pull origin main     to sync..
git pull origin b11 
